00054 /*
00055  * The following macro is provided for backward compatibility only.  If you
00056  * are a new user of netCDF, then you may safely ignore it.  If, however,
00057  * you have an existing archive of netCDF files that use default
00058  * floating-point fill values, then you should know that the definition of
00059  * the default floating-point fill values changed with version 2.3 of the
00060  * netCDF package.  Prior to this release, the default floating-point fill
00061  * values were not very portable:  their correct behavior depended not only
00062  * upon the particular platform, but also upon the compilation
00063  * environment.  This led to the definition of new, default floating-point
00064  * fill values that are portable across all platforms and compilation
00065  * environments.  If you wish, however, to obtain the old, non-portable
00066  * floating-point fill values, then the following macro should have a true
00067  * value PRIOR TO BUILDING THE netCDF LIBRARY.
00068  *
00069  * Implementation details are contained in the section below on fill values.
00070  */
00071 #define NC_OLD_FILLVALUES   0
00072 
00073 /*
00074  *  Fill values
00075  * These values are stuffed into newly allocated space as appropriate.
00076  * The hope is that one might use these to notice that a particular datum
00077  * has not been set.
00078  */
00079 
00080 #define FILL_BYTE   ((char)-127)        /* Largest Negative value */
00081 #define FILL_CHAR   ((char)0)
00082 #define FILL_SHORT  ((short)-32767)
00083 #define FILL_LONG   ((long)-2147483647)
00084 
00085 #if !NC_OLD_FILLVALUES
00086 
00087 #   define FILL_FLOAT   9.9692099683868690e+36 /* near 15 * 2^119 */
00088 #   define FILL_DOUBLE  9.9692099683868690e+36
00089 
00090 #else   /* NC_OLD_FILLVALUES below */
00091 
00092 /*
00093  * This section is provided for backward compatibility only.  Using
00094  * XDR infinities for floating-point fill values has caused more problems
00095  * than it has solved.  We encourage you to define your own data-specific
00096  * fill values rather than use default ones (see `_FillValue' below).
00097  * If, however, you *must* use default fill values, then you should use
00098  * the above fill values rather than the ones in this section.
00099  */
00100 
00101 /*
00102  * XDR_F_INFINITY is a float value whose EXTERNAL (xdr)
00103  * represention is ieee floating infinity.
00104  * XDR_D_INFINITY is a double value whose EXTERNAL (xdr)
00105  * represention is ieee double floating point infinity.
00106  * These are used as default fill values below.
00107  *
00108  * This section shows three techniques for setting these:
00109  *  Direct assignment (vax, cray) - works for non IEEE machines
00110  *      Doesn't work when IEEE machines don't allow
00111  *      float or double constants whose values are infinity.
00112  *  Use of a union (preferred portable method) - should work on
00113  *      any ANSI compiler with IEEE floating point representations,
00114  *      modulo byte order and sizeof() considerations.
00115  *  Use of pointer puns - may work with many older compilers
00116  *      which don't allow intialization of unions.
00117  *      Often doesn't work with compilers which have strict
00118  *      alignment rules.
00119  */ 
00120 
00121     /* Direct assignment. All cases should be mutually exclusive */
00122 
00123 #ifdef vax
00124 #define XDR_D_INFINITY  1.7014118346046923e+38
00125 #define XDR_F_INFINITY  1.70141173e+38
00126 #endif /* vax */
00127 
00128 #ifdef cray
00129 #define XDR_D_INFINITY  1.797693134862313000e+308
00130 #define XDR_F_INFINITY  XDR_D_INFINITY
00131 #endif /* cray */
00132 
00133 #ifdef notdef /* you might want to try these, on an IEEE machine */
00134 #define XDR_D_INFINITY  1.797693134862315900e+308
00135 #define XDR_F_INFINITY  3.40282357e+38
00136 #endif
00137 
00138 #ifdef __STDC__
00139     /* Use of a union, assumes IEEE representation and 1 byte unsigned char */
00140 
00141 #ifndef    XDR_D_INFINITY
00142 #define USE_D_UNION
00143      union xdr_d_union {unsigned char bb[8]; double dd;} ;
00144      extern union xdr_d_union xdr_d_infs ;  /* instantiated in array.c */
00145 #define XDR_D_INFINITY    (xdr_d_infs.dd)
00146 #endif /* !XDR_D_INFINITY */
00147 
00148 #ifndef    XDR_F_INFINITY
00149 #define USE_F_UNION
00150      union xdr_f_union {unsigned char bb[4]; float ff;} ;
00151      extern union xdr_f_union xdr_f_infs ;  /* instantiated in array.c */
00152 #define  XDR_F_INFINITY    (xdr_f_infs.ff)
00153 #endif /* !XDR_F_INFINITY */
00154 
00155 
00156 #else /* __STDC__ */
00157     /* Use of a pointer pun, assumes IEEE representation, 4 byte long */
00158 
00159 #ifndef    XDR_D_INFINITY
00160 #define USE_D_LONG_PUN
00161      extern long xdr_d_infinity[] ;  /* instantiated in array.c */
00162 #define XDR_D_INFINITY *(double *)xdr_d_infinity
00163 #endif /* !XDR_D_INFINITY */
00164 
00165 #ifndef    XDR_F_INFINITY
00166 #define USE_F_LONG_PUN
00167      extern long xdr_f_infinity ;  /* instantiated in array.c */
00168 #define XDR_F_INFINITY *((float *)&xdr_f_infinity)
00169 #endif /* !XDR_F_INFINITY */
00170 
00171 #endif /* __STDC__ */
00172 
00173 /* End of INFINITY           section */
00174 
00175 #define FILL_FLOAT  XDR_F_INFINITY  /* IEEE Infinity */
00176 #define FILL_DOUBLE XDR_D_INFINITY
00177 
00178 #endif  /* NC_OLD_FILLVALUES above */

00180 /*
00181  *  masks for the struct NC flags field; passed in as 'mode' arg to
00182  * nccreate and ncopen.
00183  *
00184  */
00185 #define NC_RDWR  1      /* read/write, 0 => readonly */
00186 #define NC_CREAT 2      /* in create phase, cleared by ncendef */
00187 #define NC_EXCL  4      /* on create, don't destroy existing file */
00188 #define NC_INDEF 8      /* in define mode, cleared by ncendef */
00189 #define NC_NSYNC 0x10   /* synchronise numrecs on change */
00190 #define NC_HSYNC 0x20   /* synchronise whole header on change */
00191 #define NC_NDIRTY 0x40  /* numrecs has changed */
00192 #define NC_HDIRTY 0x80  /* header info has changed */
00193 #define NC_NOFILL 0x100 /* Don't fill vars on endef and increase of record */
00194 #define NC_LINK 0x8000  /* isa link */
00195 
00196 #define NC_FILL 0   /* argument to ncsetfill to clear NC_NOFILL */
00197

00201 #define NC_NOWRITE   0
